 <div class="leftline" ><p>21 August 2013<br />Neasan ONeill</p> </div>
</div>

<h1>BioVeL: The Perfect Cloud User Candidate</h1>



<!--  optional summary div  -->
<div id="summary"><p>The CloudCaps study has released its first report and highlighted the BioVeL community as one that could use the EGI Federated Cloud to its fullest potential. The two are now collaborating to optimise the software BioVeL uses and demonstrate how cloud technologies could make web services and workflows sustainable for the long term for biodiversity research in Europe.</p></div>
<!--  end optional summary div  -->


 <p><a href="http://www.biovel.eu/" target="_blank">BioVeL</a> provide a virtual e-laboratory for biodiversity researchers, helping their users access and analyse large data sets from a wide range of sources with computerised workflows. They are also one of the pioneer users of the <a href="/infrastructure/cloud/" target="_blank">Federated Cloud</a>. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve been working with EGI since 2011 and were happy to be one of the first people to get on and test their Federated Cloud offering,&rdquo; says Alex Hardisty, BioVeL&rsquo;s Coordinator &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve had some great successes with enabling the openModeller service on the EGI Federated Cloud and we were very happy when CloudCaps chose us as a use case in their study&rdquo;.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.biovel.eu/" target="_blank"><img align="right" width="142" vspace="5" hspace="5" height="189" src="/export/sites/egi/images_logos/BioVelLogoLowResSCREEN.jpg" alt="BioVelLogoLowResSCREEN" id="iimg_-1644340921" /></a>CloudCaps is one of the <a href="http://wiki.egi.eu/wiki/Overview_of_Funded_Virtual_Team_projects" target="_blank">EGI-funded mini-projects</a>, their aim is to help the community create scientific applications that are cloud-ready. &ldquo;Clouds can give you quick results, just package up your application as you would run it on a single computer and deploy it on a load of machines &lsquo;in the cloud&rsquo;.&rdquo; explains Björn Hagemeier from CloudCaps &ldquo;You may speed up your work, but it&rsquo;s not a clever way of using the potential of the cloud, you need to look at how you can optimise your work and usage of resources.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The first step for CloudCaps was choosing and analysing a set of use cases, helping improve them for running on the Federated Cloud. These experiences would then be used to compile a set of best practices for future, and existing, users.  &ldquo;We thought the easiest way to understand how best the EGI community could use the Federated Cloud was to start with concrete examples,&rdquo; explains Björn &ldquo;so we chose five communities to investigate how they could best make use of the cloud&rdquo;. These use cases covered a wide range of areas including biomedical research, physics, language and literature studies and biodiversity.</p>
<p>There isn&rsquo;t just one way to optimise software for the cloud. Knowing where bottlenecks are and what really affects the performance is vital. For example an application might be capable of running on a single machine over a large dataset but it creates massive temporary files. So instead of splitting the job over many machines you just use one machine and request more short-term storage space for the temporary files. &ldquo;Using exactly what you need when you need it is what clouds are all about.&rdquo; says Björn &ldquo;And the openModeller software used by BioVeL was perfectly set up to exploit this way of working&rdquo;.</p>
<p><a href="http://appdb.egi.eu/store/software/openmodeller" target="_blank"><img align="right" width="287" vspace="5" hspace="5" height="89" src="/export/sites/egi/images_logos/openModeller.png" alt="openModeller" id="iimg_-1140926973" /></a> openModeller is an ecological niche modelling framework that helps biodiversity researchers to predict and understand the distribution of plant and animal species across the world under different environmental conditions. For the last two years the Brazilian organisation <a href="http://www.cria.org.br/" target="_blank">CRIA</a> (Centro de Referência em Informação Ambiental) has been working with the <a href="http://www.eubrazilopenbio.eu" target="_blank">EUBrazilOpenBio </a>project and BioVeL to get openModeller ready for cloud deployment. &ldquo;Ecological niche modelling is being increasingly used by the scientific community and we believe that this field can greatly benefit from cloud computing technologies, especially in complex experiments involving multiple species, algorithms and environmental scenarios.&ldquo; explains Renato De Giovanni from CRIA &rdquo;I&rsquo;m excited to be part of this effort and it&rsquo;s good to see that it will also benefit the wider EGI community.&rdquo;</p>
<p>BioVeL and EUBrazilOpenBio are not the only benefactor, CloudCaps are also working with <a href="http://www.wenmr.eu/" target="_blank">WeNMR</a> to optimise their work. They hope to have the software for both groups optimised, tested and deployed soon.</p>
<p>The work will be presented at two conferences in September, the <a href="https://tf2013.egi.eu/" target="_blank">EGI Technical Forum</a> in Madrid and the <a href="Biodiversity Informatics Horizons 2013 conference" target="_blank">Biodiversity Informatics Horizons 2013</a> conference in Rome.</p>
 

 
 

   

  
  
  
 



